<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-615-099  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 615 099.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Nov 12 1990 v36 n1835 p16(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>State officials cite 'new evidence,' ask FCC to revise Nynexdecree. (the New York Attorney General and New York ConsumerProtection Board charge Nynex with violating the CommunicationsAct and FCC rules)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connelly, Joanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The New York (state) Attorney General and Consumer ProtectionBoard ask the US Federal Communications Commission to revise itsrecent consent decree with Nynex Corp following discovery ofevidence showing that the decree effectively sanctions allegedviolations of the Communications Act.andP;  Allegations were raised ina New York rate case that indicate New York Telephone may haveviolated the Communications Act and FCC regulations to a muchgreater and more serious extent than thought at the time thesettlement was adopted.andP;  Nynex reportedly used its former centralpurchasing unit, MECO, to transfer telephone unit purchases toother unregulated Nynex affiliates serving as suppliers even whenthere was no benefit to the phone companies.andP;  A former MECOexecutive cited a case in which Nynex Business Centers received 70percent of an award even though it was the highest pricedsupplier.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   NYNEX Corp. (Investigations).andO;Ticker:    NYN.andO;Topic:     State GovernmentInvestigationsEquipment AcquisitionGovernment RegulationNew YorkCommunications Service SuppliersPricing PolicyBell Regional Holding CompaniesUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionTelephone companiesNew York (State). Consumer Protection BoardNew York (State). Department of Law.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>